{"title_page": "\u00c1sger\u00f0ur J\u00fan\u00edusd\u00f3ttir", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Multiple issues|{{citation style|date=September 2018}}{{BLP sources|date=September 2018}}}}\n\n{{Icelandic name|\u00c1sger\u00f0ur ''or'' \u00c1sa|female}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name          = \u00c1sger\u00f0ur J\u00fan\u00edusd\u00f3ttir\n| image         =\n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \u00c1sa J\u00fan\u00edus\n| caption       = \n| pseudonym     = \n| birth_name    = \u00c1sger\u00f0ur J\u00fan\u00edusd\u00f3ttir\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1968|09|26}}\n| birth_place   = [[Reykjav\u00edk]], Iceland\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| resting_place = \n| occupation    = Singer<br>[[mezzo-soprano]]<br>performer\n| nationality   = Icelandic\n| ethnicity     = \n| citizenship   = \n| education     = \n| alma_mater    = \n| period        = \n| genre         = Opera<br>[[Contemporary music]]\n| subject       = \n| movement      = \n| notableworks  = ''Minn heimur og \u00feinn'' (2001)<br>''\u00cd r\u00f6kkri'' (2006)<br>Langt fyrir utan ystu sk\u00f3ga (2011)\n| spouse        = \n| partner       = \n| children      = \n| relatives     = \n| influences    = \n| influenced    = \n| awards        = \n| signature     = \n| signature_alt = \n| website       = \n| portaldisp    = \n}}\n\n'''\u00c1sger\u00f0ur J\u00fan\u00edusd\u00f3ttir''' (born 26 September 1968) is an Icelandic singer, [[mezzo-soprano]], and performer who has performed on stage and released music in Iceland and abroad.\n\n== Biography ==\n\u00c1sger\u00f0ur J\u00fan\u00edusd\u00f3ttir, mezzo-soprano, has appeared as a singer and actress in Iceland and abroad. In her career she has focused on 20th- and 21st-century Icelandic music and premiered works by contemporary composers, including [[J\u00f3runn Vi\u00f0ar]], [[Atli Heimir Sveinsson]], [[Haukur T\u00f3masson]], [[Kar\u00f3l\u00edna Eir\u00edksd\u00f3ttir]], and Ragnhildur G\u00edslad\u00f3ttir, as well as worked with different music ensembles such as the English [[Brodsky Quartet]].{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\nShe has released three CDs on the Smekkleysa label. Her first two Minn heimur og \u00feinn (Tapestry of dreams, 2001), which contains songs and poems by Icelandic women and \u00cd r\u00f6kkri (At Twilight, 2006), containing songs by [[Magn\u00fas Bl\u00f6ndal J\u00f3hannsson]], were both nominated for the Icelandic Music Award.{{citation needed|date=September 2018}} Her latest CD, Langt fyrir utan ystu sk\u00f3ga (Far Beyond the Remotest Forests), with songs by [[Bj\u00f6rk]] Gu\u00f0mundsd\u00f3ttir, Gunnar Reynir Sveinsson and Magn\u00fas Bl\u00f6ndal J\u00f3hannsson was released in the summer of 2011.\n\nAmong the parts that \u00c1sger\u00f0ur has sung on stage are those of [[Carmen]] in [[Georges Bizet]]\u2019s opera of the same name at the [[Reykjav\u00edk City Theatre]] (2006), Magnus-Maria (2014) and Skuggaleikur (Play of Shadows, 2006) by Kar\u00f3l\u00edna Eir\u00edksd\u00f3ttir and [[Sj\u00f3n]], and Wide Slumber by [[Valgeir Sigur\u00f0sson]] (2014). She has also acted and sung in the mono-opera The Medium (2009) by sir [[Peter Maxwell Davies]] and appeared as actress in the theatre productions Common Nonsense (2004) and Ball of Yarn (2009).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LobOoM_locY&t=36s |title=\u00c1TTA RADDIR: \u00c1sger\u00f0ur J\u00fan\u00edusd\u00f3ttir TV Documentary Broadcast 11.02.2011 |work=Web |publisher=R\u00daV (The Icelandic National Broadcasting Service) |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?pageId=4164551 |title=M\u00c9R FELLUR VEL A\u00d0 FARA M\u00cdNAR EIGIN LEI\u00d0IR Profile interview published 26.06.2007 |work=Web |publisher=Morgunbla\u00f0i\u00f0 |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2011 she took part in \"Your Country Does Not Exist\" by [[Libia Castro and \u00d3lafur \u00d3lafsson]], Iceland's official Icelandic contribution to the [[Venice Biennale]], performing a political statement on a gondola sailing Venice.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.flashartonline.com/article/libia-castro-olafur-olafsson/ |title=Libia Castro & \u00d3lafur \u00d3lafsson |work=Web |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Works ==\n\n=== Discography ===\n* ''Minn heimur og \u00feinn'' Songs and poems by Icelandic women (\"Tapestry of Dreams\", Smekkleysa, 2001)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?gegnirId=000516678 |title=\u00c1ger\u00f0ur J\u00fan\u00edusd\u00f3ttir |work=Web |publisher=VERA |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?pageId=3431870 |title=T\u00f3nlist \u00edslenskra kvenna |work=Web |publisher=Morgubla\u00f0i\u00f0 |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gramophone.co.uk/review/sigurbj%C3%B6rnsson-sk%C3%A1lholt-mass|title=A quartet of discs reveal the tremendous variety and richness of Icelandic music|author=Ivan Moody|date=November 2003|website=Gramophone|accessdate=5 September 2018}}</ref>\n* ''\u00cd r\u00f6kkri'' Songs by Magn\u00fas Bl\u00f6ndal J\u00f3hannsson (\"At Twilight\", Smekkleysa, 2006)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?pageId=3928940 |title=\u00cd r\u00f6kkri Magn\u00fasar og \u00c1sger\u00f0ar |work=Web |publisher=Fr\u00e9ttabla\u00f0i\u00f0 |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Langt fyrir utan ystu sk\u00f3ga'' Songs by Bj\u00f6rk Gu\u00f0mundsd\u00f3ttir, Gunnar Reynir Sveinsson, Magn\u00fas Bl\u00f6ndal J\u00f3hannsson (\"Far Beyond the Remotest Forests\", Smekkleysa, 2011)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?pageId=5368695 |title=T\u00f3nsk\u00e1ld me\u00f0 s\u00e9rst\u00f6\u00f0u |work=Web |publisher=Morgunbla\u00f0i\u00f0 |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Stage ===\n* ''Common Nonsense'', a play by John Wrigth and the troupe (Reykjav\u00edk City Theatre, 2003)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?pageId=3483499 |title=Tilgangslaus gagnsemi |work=Web |publisher=Morgunbla\u00f0i\u00f0 |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Gu\u00f0r\u00fans 4th Song'', an opera by Haukur T\u00f3masson (B\u00e5stad Chamber Music Festival, 2005)\n* ''Carmen'', an opera by George Bizet (Reykjavik City Theatre, 2006)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?pageId=5543714 |title=G\u00e1lan Carmen |work=Web |publisher=DV |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Madonna Furiosa'', an opera by [[Bertil Palmar Johansen]] (The Nordic House, Reykjav\u00edk, 2006)\n* ''Skuggaleikur'', an opera by Kar\u00f3l\u00edna Eir\u00edksd\u00f3ttir (The Icelandic Opera, Reykjav\u00edk 2006)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?pageId=4145773 |title=Um skuggann og sk\u00e1ldi\u00f0 |work=Web |publisher=Morgunbla\u00f0i\u00f0 |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>\n* ''The Medium'', an opera by Peter Maxwell Davies (The Reykjav\u00edk Arts Festival, Reykjav\u00edk 2009)\n* ''Hnykill'', a site specific play by Margr\u00e9t Vilhj\u00e1lmsd\u00f3ttir and the troupe. (Nor\u00f0urp\u00f3llinn, Reykjav\u00edk 2009)\n* ''Lange Nacht der Opera'' an installation of three works at the [[Volksb\u00fchne]] (Berlin, 2011)<ref>{{cite web |url= http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?pageId=4181335 |title=\u00c1sger\u00f0ur J\u00fan\u00edusd\u00f3ttir syngur \u00e1 Volksb\u00fchne |work=Web |publisher=Morgunbla\u00f0i\u00f0 |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Wide Slumber'' an opera by Valgeir Sigur\u00f0sson (The Reykjav\u00edk Arts Festival, Reykjav\u00edk 2014)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?pageId=6077241 |title=Sameina fi\u00f0rildafr\u00e6\u00f0i og svefnranns\u00f3knir |work=Web |publisher=Morgunbla\u00f0i\u00f0 |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Magnus Maria: An opera about the right gender'', an opera by Kar\u00f3l\u00edna Eir\u00edksd\u00f3ttir (Mariehamn, 2014)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.katrina.ax/magnus-maria-opera-om-ratt-kon |title=Magnus-Maria&nbsp;\u2013 en opera om r\u00e4tt k\u00f6n |work=Web |publisher=Kulturforeningen Katarina |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dn.se/kultur-noje/scenrecensioner/magnus-maria-en-opera-om-ratt-kon-pa-kulturhuset-stadsteatern-klarascenen/ |title=Magnus-Maria p\u00e5 Kulturhuset Stadsteatern, Klarascenen |work=Web |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Contributions ===\n* ''Svo \u00e1 j\u00f6r\u00f0u sem \u00e1 himni'', \"[[As in Heaven]]\" soundtrack by [[Hilmar \u00d6rn Hilmarsson]] to the film by Krist\u00edn J\u00f3hannesd\u00f3ttir.\n* ''Glands'', a song on the album \"Hi-Camp meets Lo-fi\" by Dip ([[J\u00f3hann J\u00f3hannsson]] & [[Sigtryggur Baldursson]]).\n* ''Sense of Reason'', a song on the album \"In Cod We Trust\" by [[Ghostigital]] ([[Einar \u00d6rn Benediktsson]] & [[Curver]]).\n* ''Les myst\u00e8res du Sn\u00e6fellsj\u00f6kull'', the song \"Aria\" by Magn\u00fas Bl\u00f6ndal J\u00f3hannsson features in the soundtrack of the documentary by [[Jean-Michel Roux]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mezzaninefilms.com/les-mysteres-du-snaefellsjokull.html |title=Les myst\u00e8res du Sn\u00e6fellsj\u00f6kul |work=Web |publisher=Mezzanine Films |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Litlu b\u00f6rnin leika s\u00e9r'' and ''Kindur jarma \u00ed kofunum'', two children songs on the album \"Hva\u00f0 \u00e1 a\u00f0 gera?\" by Margr\u00e9t \u00d6rn\u00f3lfsd\u00f3ttir.\n* ''Motorlab #2'' A compilation from the [[Kitchen Motors]] events in Reykjav\u00edk. \u00c1sger\u00f0ur J\u00fan\u00edusd\u00f3ttir sings in excerpts from the chamber opera Kisa by [[M\u00fam]] and Sj\u00f3n.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?pageId=1968738 |title=Hver er \u00feessi kisa? |work=Web |publisher=Morgunbla\u00f0i\u00f0 |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCjfFwejidnLZlS3udY5ZW_Q Official YouTube Channel]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:J\u00fan\u00edusd\u00f3ttir, \u00c1sgerdur}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Reykjav\u00edk|\u00c1sger\u00f0ur J\u00fan\u00edusd\u00f3ttir]]\n[[Category:Icelandic operatic sopranos|\u00c1sger\u00f0ur J\u00fan\u00edusd\u00f3ttir]]\n[[Category:Icelandic female singers|\u00c1sger\u00f0ur J\u00fan\u00edusd\u00f3ttir]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Multiple issues|{{citation style|date=September 2018}}{{BLP sources|date=September 2018}}}}\n\n{{Icelandic name|\u00c1sger\u00f0ur ''or'' \u00c1sa|female}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name          = \u00c1sger\u00f0ur J\u00fan\u00edusd\u00f3ttir\n| image         =\n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \u00c1sa J\u00fan\u00edus\n| caption       = \n| pseudonym     = \n| birth_name    = \u00c1sger\u00f0ur J\u00fan\u00edusd\u00f3ttir\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1968|09|26}}\n| birth_place   = [[Reykjav\u00edk]], Iceland\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| resting_place = \n| occupation    = Singer<br>[[mezzo-soprano]]<br>performer\n| nationality   = Icelandic\n| ethnicity     = \n| citizenship   = \n| education     = \n| alma_mater    = \n| period        = \n| genre         = Opera<br>[[Contemporary music]]\n| subject       = \n| movement      = \n| notableworks  = ''Minn heimur og \u00feinn'' (2001)<br>''\u00cd r\u00f6kkri'' (2006)<br>Langt fyrir utan ystu sk\u00f3ga (2011)\n| spouse        = \n| partner       = \n| children      = \n| relatives     = \n| influences    = \n| influenced    = \n| awards        = \n| signature     = \n| signature_alt = \n| website       = \n| portaldisp    = \n}}\n\n'''\u00c1sger\u00f0ur J\u00fan\u00edusd\u00f3ttir''' (born 26 September 1968) is an Icelandic singer, [[mezzo-soprano]], and performer who has performed on stage and released music in Iceland and abroad.\n\n== Biography ==\n\u00c1sger\u00f0ur J\u00fan\u00edusd\u00f3ttir, mezzo-soprano, has appeared as a singer and actress in Iceland and abroad. In her career she has focused on 20th- and 21st-century Icelandic music and premiered works by contemporary composers, including [[J\u00f3runn Vi\u00f0ar]], [[Atli Heimir Sveinsson]], [[Haukur T\u00f3masson]], [[Kar\u00f3l\u00edna Eir\u00edksd\u00f3ttir]], and Ragnhildur G\u00edslad\u00f3ttir, as well as worked with different music ensembles such as the English [[Brodsky Quartet]].{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\nShe has released three CDs on the Smekkleysa label. Her first two Minn heimur og \u00feinn (Tapestry of dreams, 2001), which contains songs and poems by Icelandic women and \u00cd r\u00f6kkri (At Twilight, 2006), containing songs by [[Magn\u00fas Bl\u00f6ndal J\u00f3hannsson]], were both nominated for the Icelandic Music Award.{{citation needed|date=September 2018}} Her latest CD, Langt fyrir utan ystu sk\u00f3ga (Far Beyond the Remotest Forests), with songs by [[Bj\u00f6rk]] Gu\u00f0mundsd\u00f3ttir, Gunnar Reynir Sveinsson and Magn\u00fas Bl\u00f6ndal J\u00f3hannsson was released in the summer of 2011.\n\nAmong the parts that \u00c1sger\u00f0ur has sung on stage are those of [[Carmen]] in [[George Bizet]]\u2019s opera of the same name at the [[Reykjav\u00edk City Theatre]] (2006), Magnus-Maria (2014) and Skuggaleikur (Play of Shadows, 2006) by Kar\u00f3l\u00edna Eir\u00edksd\u00f3ttir and [[Sj\u00f3n]], and Wide Slumber by [[Valgeir Sigur\u00f0sson]] (2014). She has also acted and sung in the mono-opera The Medium (2009) by sir [[Peter Maxwell Davies]] and appeared as actress in the theatre productions Common Nonsense (2004) and Ball of Yarn (2009).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LobOoM_locY&t=36s |title=\u00c1TTA RADDIR: \u00c1sger\u00f0ur J\u00fan\u00edusd\u00f3ttir TV Documentary Broadcast 11.02.2011 |work=Web |publisher=R\u00daV (The Icelandic National Broadcasting Service) |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?pageId=4164551 |title=M\u00c9R FELLUR VEL A\u00d0 FARA M\u00cdNAR EIGIN LEI\u00d0IR Profile interview published 26.06.2007 |work=Web |publisher=Morgunbla\u00f0i\u00f0 |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2011 she took part in \"Your Country Does Not Exist\" by [[Libia Castro and \u00d3lafur \u00d3lafsson]], Iceland's official Icelandic contribution to the [[Venice Biennale]], performing a political statement on a gondola sailing Venice.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.flashartonline.com/article/libia-castro-olafur-olafsson/ |title=Libia Castro & \u00d3lafur \u00d3lafsson |work=Web |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Works ==\n\n=== Discography ===\n* ''Minn heimur og \u00feinn'' Songs and poems by Icelandic women (\"Tapestry of Dreams\", Smekkleysa, 2001)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?gegnirId=000516678 |title=\u00c1ger\u00f0ur J\u00fan\u00edusd\u00f3ttir |work=Web |publisher=VERA |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?pageId=3431870 |title=T\u00f3nlist \u00edslenskra kvenna |work=Web |publisher=Morgubla\u00f0i\u00f0 |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gramophone.co.uk/review/sigurbj%C3%B6rnsson-sk%C3%A1lholt-mass|title=A quartet of discs reveal the tremendous variety and richness of Icelandic music|author=Ivan Moody|date=November 2003|website=Gramophone|accessdate=5 September 2018}}</ref>\n* ''\u00cd r\u00f6kkri'' Songs by Magn\u00fas Bl\u00f6ndal J\u00f3hannsson (\"At Twilight\", Smekkleysa, 2006)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?pageId=3928940 |title=\u00cd r\u00f6kkri Magn\u00fasar og \u00c1sger\u00f0ar |work=Web |publisher=Fr\u00e9ttabla\u00f0i\u00f0 |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Langt fyrir utan ystu sk\u00f3ga'' Songs by Bj\u00f6rk Gu\u00f0mundsd\u00f3ttir, Gunnar Reynir Sveinsson, Magn\u00fas Bl\u00f6ndal J\u00f3hannsson (\"Far Beyond the Remotest Forests\", Smekkleysa, 2011)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?pageId=5368695 |title=T\u00f3nsk\u00e1ld me\u00f0 s\u00e9rst\u00f6\u00f0u |work=Web |publisher=Morgunbla\u00f0i\u00f0 |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Stage ===\n* ''Common Nonsense'', a play by John Wrigth and the troupe (Reykjav\u00edk City Theatre, 2003)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?pageId=3483499 |title=Tilgangslaus gagnsemi |work=Web |publisher=Morgunbla\u00f0i\u00f0 |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Gu\u00f0r\u00fans 4th Song'', an opera by Haukur T\u00f3masson (B\u00e5stad Chamber Music Festival, 2005)\n* ''Carmen'', an opera by George Bizet (Reykjavik City Theatre, 2006)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?pageId=5543714 |title=G\u00e1lan Carmen |work=Web |publisher=DV |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Madonna Furiosa'', an opera by [[Bertil Palmar Johansen]] (The Nordic House, Reykjav\u00edk, 2006)\n* ''Skuggaleikur'', an opera by Kar\u00f3l\u00edna Eir\u00edksd\u00f3ttir (The Icelandic Opera, Reykjav\u00edk 2006)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?pageId=4145773 |title=Um skuggann og sk\u00e1ldi\u00f0 |work=Web |publisher=Morgunbla\u00f0i\u00f0 |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>\n* ''The Medium'', an opera by Peter Maxwell Davies (The Reykjav\u00edk Arts Festival, Reykjav\u00edk 2009)\n* ''Hnykill'', a site specific play by Margr\u00e9t Vilhj\u00e1lmsd\u00f3ttir and the troupe. (Nor\u00f0urp\u00f3llinn, Reykjav\u00edk 2009)\n* ''Lange Nacht der Opera'' an installation of three works at the [[Volksb\u00fchne]] (Berlin, 2011)<ref>{{cite web |url= http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?pageId=4181335 |title=\u00c1sger\u00f0ur J\u00fan\u00edusd\u00f3ttir syngur \u00e1 Volksb\u00fchne |work=Web |publisher=Morgunbla\u00f0i\u00f0 |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Wide Slumber'' an opera by Valgeir Sigur\u00f0sson (The Reykjav\u00edk Arts Festival, Reykjav\u00edk 2014)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?pageId=6077241 |title=Sameina fi\u00f0rildafr\u00e6\u00f0i og svefnranns\u00f3knir |work=Web |publisher=Morgunbla\u00f0i\u00f0 |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Magnus Maria: An opera about the right gender'', an opera by Kar\u00f3l\u00edna Eir\u00edksd\u00f3ttir (Mariehamn, 2014)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.katrina.ax/magnus-maria-opera-om-ratt-kon |title=Magnus-Maria&nbsp;\u2013 en opera om r\u00e4tt k\u00f6n |work=Web |publisher=Kulturforeningen Katarina |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dn.se/kultur-noje/scenrecensioner/magnus-maria-en-opera-om-ratt-kon-pa-kulturhuset-stadsteatern-klarascenen/ |title=Magnus-Maria p\u00e5 Kulturhuset Stadsteatern, Klarascenen |work=Web |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Contributions ===\n* ''Svo \u00e1 j\u00f6r\u00f0u sem \u00e1 himni'', \"[[As in Heaven]]\" soundtrack by [[Hilmar \u00d6rn Hilmarsson]] to the film by Krist\u00edn J\u00f3hannesd\u00f3ttir.\n* ''Glands'', a song on the album \"Hi-Camp meets Lo-fi\" by Dip ([[J\u00f3hann J\u00f3hannsson]] & [[Sigtryggur Baldursson]]).\n* ''Sense of Reason'', a song on the album \"In Cod We Trust\" by [[Ghostigital]] ([[Einar \u00d6rn Benediktsson]] & [[Curver]]).\n* ''Les myst\u00e8res du Sn\u00e6fellsj\u00f6kull'', the song \"Aria\" by Magn\u00fas Bl\u00f6ndal J\u00f3hannsson features in the soundtrack of the documentary by [[Jean-Michel Roux]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mezzaninefilms.com/les-mysteres-du-snaefellsjokull.html |title=Les myst\u00e8res du Sn\u00e6fellsj\u00f6kul |work=Web |publisher=Mezzanine Films |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Litlu b\u00f6rnin leika s\u00e9r'' and ''Kindur jarma \u00ed kofunum'', two children songs on the album \"Hva\u00f0 \u00e1 a\u00f0 gera?\" by Margr\u00e9t \u00d6rn\u00f3lfsd\u00f3ttir.\n* ''Motorlab #2'' A compilation from the [[Kitchen Motors]] events in Reykjav\u00edk. \u00c1sger\u00f0ur J\u00fan\u00edusd\u00f3ttir sings in excerpts from the chamber opera Kisa by [[M\u00fam]] and Sj\u00f3n.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?pageId=1968738 |title=Hver er \u00feessi kisa? |work=Web |publisher=Morgunbla\u00f0i\u00f0 |accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCjfFwejidnLZlS3udY5ZW_Q Official YouTube Channel]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:J\u00fan\u00edusd\u00f3ttir, \u00c1sgerdur}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Reykjav\u00edk|\u00c1sger\u00f0ur J\u00fan\u00edusd\u00f3ttir]]\n[[Category:Icelandic operatic sopranos|\u00c1sger\u00f0ur J\u00fan\u00edusd\u00f3ttir]]\n[[Category:Icelandic female singers|\u00c1sger\u00f0ur J\u00fan\u00edusd\u00f3ttir]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "EdmundT", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography:Spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%81sger%C3%B0ur_J%C3%BAn%C3%ADusd%C3%B3ttir"}
{"title_page": "I believe that we will win!", "text_new": "\"'''I believe that we will win!'''\" is a [[chant]] commonly performed at sporting events. Originating in the [[Naval Academy Preparatory School]], it became a tradition among fans and students of the [[United States Naval Academy]], with other schools later also adapting the phrase. In 2014, the chant gained national recognition as a rallying call among [[United States men's national soccer team]] (USMNT) fans for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]], becoming an unofficial motto of [[The American Outlaws]] supporters' group.\n\nThe chant is a [[call and response]] interaction between two parties. It begins with one call of \"I,\" \"I believe,\" followed by \"I believe that,\" and \"I believe that we,\" before concluding with repeated shouts of \"I believe that we will win!\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theamericanoutlaws.com/chants|title=American Outlaws chants|work=[[The American Outlaws]]|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:US Navy 031206-N-9693M-513 The U.S. Naval Academy Brigade of Midshipmen cheers for their football team during the 104th Army Navy Game.jpg|thumb|The Brigade of Midshipmen cheer during the 2003 Army\u2013Navy Game. In the buildup to the game, the school sold T-shirts containing \"I believe that we will win!\".<ref name=\"U.S. soccer fans\u2019 \u2018I believe that we will win\u2019 chant started with Navy football\" />]]\nIn 1998, Naval Academy Preparatory School (NAPS) student Jay Rodriguez was assigned to create a chant to be used by his platoon and came up with \"I believe that we will win!\". It was first used during a NAPS basketball game against the [[United States Military Academy Preparatory School]] in [[Newport, Rhode Island]]. A year later, now a Naval Academy student, Rodriguez taught it to his classmate, cheerleader Corey Strong, who began using it during the 1999 [[Army\u2013Navy Game]]; in the fourth quarter of the 19\u20139 [[Navy Midshipmen football|Navy]] victory, Strong led the 4,000-student Brigade of Midshipmen in the chant.<ref name=\"USNA History and Traditions\">{{cite new|url=http://www.navysports.com/this-is-navy/history.html|title=USNA History and Traditions (Summer 2013)|work=[[Navy Midshipmen]]|accessdate=March 24, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170619205448/http://www.navysports.com/this-is-navy/history.html|archive-date=June 19, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2003, the Midshipmen team showed marked improvement over their 3\u201330 record in the last three years; during a game against the No. 25-ranked [[Air Force Falcons football|Air Force Falcons]] at [[FedExField]], Navy students began reciting the chant as the Midshipmen won 28\u201325. In preparation for the Army\u2013Navy Game later that year, Navy sold T-shirts with the phrase written on them.<ref name=\"U.S. soccer fans\u2019 \u2018I believe that we will win\u2019 chant started with Navy football\">{{cite news|last=Bonesteel|first=Matt|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/soccer-insider/wp/2014/07/01/u-s-soccer-fans-i-believe-that-we-will-win-chant-started-with-navy-football/|title=U.S. soccer fans\u2019 \u2018I believe that we will win\u2019 chant started with Navy football|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=July 1, 2014|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref> The chant is currently performed by midshipmen in the closing stages of a victory.<ref name=\"USNA History and Traditions\" />\n\nThe chant eventually spread to other college sports, with fans of the [[Utah State Aggies men's basketball]] team adopting its usage in 2009.<ref name=\"'I believe that we will win' could be trademarked by San Diego State\">{{cite news|last=Stephens|first=Matt|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/college/2014/07/07/i-believe-that-we-will-win-chant-could-be-trademarked-by-san-diego-state/12289091/|title='I believe that we will win' could be trademarked by San Diego State|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=July 7, 2014|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref> [[The Show (SDSU student section)|The Show]] of [[San Diego State University]] and [[Harvard Crimson]] students also performed it during games. Fans of various soccer clubs have also recited it, including the [[New York Red Bulls]] of [[Major League Soccer]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Brennan|first=Eamonn|url=http://www.espn.com/blog/collegebasketballnation/post/_/id/39091/coolest-chant-in-the-country-began-at-navy|title=Coolest chant in the country began at Navy|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=November 17, 2011|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref> and French team [[FC Nantes]].<ref name=\"Bedoya leads Nantes fans in 'I believe that we will win!'\">{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/planet-futbol/2016/05/09/alejandro-bedoya-nantes-chant-i-believe-we-will-win|title=Watch: Bedoya leads Nantes fans in 'I believe that we will win!'|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=May 9, 2016|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref> During the [[2016 Ryder Cup]], \"[[U-S-A!]]\" chants by American fans interspersed with calls of \"I believe that we will win!\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Williams|first=Roddy|url=http://www.rydercup.com/news-media/europe/ryder-cup-under-way-0|title=On the first tee: Ryder Cup under way|publisher=[[Ryder Cup]]|date=September 30, 2016|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===United States soccer===\nAccording to Justin Brunken, co-founder of the U.S. soccer [[supporters' group]] [[The American Outlaws]], he first heard the chant during a 2011 U.S. soccer game in Kansas City. He described it as \"a chant that just grew from there and caught on and on. It resonated with the crowds across the country and became synonymous with what we believe in.\" It eventually became a rallying call by fans of the United States national men's soccer team (USMNT). For the 2014 FIFA World Cup, [[ESPN]] used the chant in two commercials promoting the Cup, one depicting The American Outlaws and the other featuring figures like [[Kevin Costner]], [[Ice Cube]] and [[Barry Sanders]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Eisenberg|first=Jeff|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/soccer-dirty-tackle/the-improbable-story-of-how-the-trendiest-chant-in-sports-began-040228934.html|title=The improbable story of how the trendiest chant in sports began|publisher=[[Yahoo! Sports]]|date=June 19, 2014|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref> The cheer was also acknowledged by members of the USMNT, with goalkeeper [[Tim Howard]] posting it on his [[Twitter]] and receiving almost 60,000 [[Twitter#Tweets|retweets]] during the 2014 World Cup,<ref>{{cite news|last=Hall|first=Matthew|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/opinion/the-conversation/sdut-i-believe-that-we-will-win-trademark-sdsu-2014jul07-htmlstory.html|title=SDSU may trademark 'I believe that we will win!'|newspaper=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]|date=July 7, 2014|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref> [[Alejandro Bedoya]] leading FC Nantes fans in it after home games,<ref name=\"Bedoya leads Nantes fans in 'I believe that we will win!'\" /> and former captain [[Landon Donovan]] doing so prior to the [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup]] final.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/extra-mustard/2015/07/05/landon-donovan-chant-video-uswnt-womens-world-cup|title=Landon Donovan leads 'I believe that we will win' chant before WWC final|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=July 5, 2015|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref> The [[United States women's national soccer team]] went on to win the Cup after defeating [[Japan women's national football team|Japan]].<ref name=\"USWNT leads crowd in \u2018I believe that we just won\u2019 chant\" />\n\nDuring the 2015 World Cup victory parade for the [[United States women's national soccer team]] (USWNT), forward [[Abby Wambach]] led fans in a modified call of \"I believe that we just won!\"<ref name=\"USWNT leads crowd in \u2018I believe that we just won\u2019 chant\">{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/planet-futbol/2015/07/07/uswnt-world-cup-victory-rally-chant-video|title=Watch: USWNT leads crowd in \u2018I believe that we just won\u2019 chant|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=July 7, 2015|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===San Diego State University trademark===\nStrong, who was taught the chant by Rodriguez, was later stationed in San Diego and earned his [[Master of Business Administration]] at San Diego State.<ref name=\"I believe that we will win the trademark\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbs8.com/story/25992071/i-believe-that-we-will-win-the-trademark|title=\"I believe that we will win\" the trademark|publisher=[[KFMB-TV]]|date=July 10, 2014|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref> In 2011, San Diego State clothing store Aztec Shops Ltd. attempted to trademark the phrase.<ref name=\"'I believe that we will win' could be trademarked by San Diego State\" /> Strong opposed the trademark, stating \"everybody would be best served if they removed their attempt to trademark the cheer\" and that the Naval Academy would be resisting it.<ref name=\"I believe that we will win the trademark\" /> In 2017, the [[Trademark Trial and Appeal Board]] rejected the trademark, saying it had been \"widely used over a long period of time by various groups.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Donahue|first=Bill|url=https://www.law360.com/articles/886683/ttab-won-t-register-i-believe-chant-as-trademark|title=TTAB Won't Register 'I Believe' Chant As Trademark|work=[[Law360]]|date=January 31, 2017|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Other sports===\nIn 2018, [[FiveThirtyEight]] referenced the chant in the title of an article about American's success in recent golf tournaments.<ref>{{cite web|last=Planos|first=Josh|url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/i-believe-that-we-will-win-at-golf/|title=I Believe That We Will Win \u2026 At Golf|publisher=[[FiveThirtyEight]]|date=July 19, 2018|accessdate=July 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Non-sports usage===\nAfter the [[death of Osama bin Laden]] in 2011, the Naval Academy celebrated with Commandant [[Robert E. Clark II]]. Clark led the midshipmen in a modified chant of \"I believe that we have won!\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Davis|first=Noah|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/osama-bin-laden-us-naval-academy-dant-i-believe-2011-5|title=US Naval Academy Students Go ABSOLUTELY NUTS Celebrating Osama Bin Laden's Death [VIDEO]|publisher=[[Business Insider]]|date=May 2, 2011|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe chant has also seen use in protest, such as during the [[Occupy Wall Street]] march in 2011. The Florida-based organization [[Dream Defenders]] adopted the phrase for protests following the 2012 [[shooting of Trayvon Martin]], used during a protest at the Florida state capital in 2012.<ref>{{cite news|last=Alvarez|first=Lisette|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/12/us/dream-defenders-arent-walking-out-on-their-florida-protest.html|title=Florida Sit-In Against \u2018Stand Your Ground\u2019|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=August 11, 2013|accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref> Phil Agnew of the Dream Defenders also led the chant during the 50th anniversary of the \"March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom\" in 2013, leading to its nationwide prominence during [[Black Lives Matter]] protests between 2012\u20132016.<ref>{{cite web|last=Morrison|first=Aaron|url=https://www.mic.com/articles/166084/black-lives-matter-inaugurates-four-years-of-resistance-with-anti-trump-disruption-protest|title=Black Lives Matter inaugurates four years of resistance with anti-Trump disruption protest|publisher=[[Mic (media company)|Mic]]|date=January 20, 2016|accessdate=February 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 13, 2020, Pitbull released a promotional single titled \"I Believe That We Will Win (World Anthem)\" (which samples the [[I believe that we will win!]] chant) in response to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]. The song inspires those affected by the COVID-19 outbreak to lift themselves up and rise above the situation. The promotional single was premiered in full on April 12 on the virtual TrillerFest, and made its TV debut on April 13 on [[Good Morning America]]. An accompanying music video was also released. Pitbull is donating all proceeds from song sales, streaming, and views to COVID-19 affiliated nonprofits.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/03/listen-to-pitbulls-new-song-i-believe-we-will-win.html|title=Pitbull Delivers a Message of Hope in New Coronavirus Jam|last=Sinha|first=Charu|work=Mashable|access-date=2020-03-28|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Sports}}\n* [[Football chant]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{United States men's national soccer team}}\n{{Navy Midshipmen football navbox}}\n{{Navy Midshipmen men's soccer navbox}}\n\n[[Category:Football songs and chants]]\n[[Category:Association football culture]]\n[[Category:United States men's national soccer team]]\n[[Category:Navy Midshipmen]]\n", "text_old": "\"'''I believe that we will win!'''\" is a [[chant]] commonly performed at sporting events. Originating in the [[Naval Academy Preparatory School]], it became a tradition among fans and students of the [[United States Naval Academy]], with other schools later also adapting the phrase. In 2014, the chant gained national recognition as a rallying call among [[United States men's national soccer team]] (USMNT) fans for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]], becoming an unofficial motto of [[The American Outlaws]] supporters' group.\n\nThe chant is a [[call and response]] interaction between two parties. It begins with one call of \"I,\" \"I believe,\" followed by \"I believe that,\" and \"I believe that we,\" before concluding with repeated shouts of \"I believe that we will win!\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theamericanoutlaws.com/chants|title=American Outlaws chants|work=[[The American Outlaws]]|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:US Navy 031206-N-9693M-513 The U.S. Naval Academy Brigade of Midshipmen cheers for their football team during the 104th Army Navy Game.jpg|thumb|The Brigade of Midshipmen cheer during the 2003 Army\u2013Navy Game. In the buildup to the game, the school sold T-shirts containing \"I believe that we will win!\".<ref name=\"U.S. soccer fans\u2019 \u2018I believe that we will win\u2019 chant started with Navy football\" />]]\nIn 1998, Naval Academy Preparatory School (NAPS) student Jay Rodriguez was assigned to create a chant to be used by his platoon and came up with \"I believe that we will win!\". It was first used during a NAPS basketball game against the [[United States Military Academy Preparatory School]] in [[Newport, Rhode Island]]. A year later, now a Naval Academy student, Rodriguez taught it to his classmate, cheerleader Corey Strong, who began using it during the 1999 [[Army\u2013Navy Game]]; in the fourth quarter of the 19\u20139 [[Navy Midshipmen football|Navy]] victory, Strong led the 4,000-student Brigade of Midshipmen in the chant.<ref name=\"USNA History and Traditions\">{{cite new|url=http://www.navysports.com/this-is-navy/history.html|title=USNA History and Traditions (Summer 2013)|work=[[Navy Midshipmen]]|accessdate=March 24, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170619205448/http://www.navysports.com/this-is-navy/history.html|archive-date=June 19, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2003, the Midshipmen team showed marked improvement over their 3\u201330 record in the last three years; during a game against the No. 25-ranked [[Air Force Falcons football|Air Force Falcons]] at [[FedExField]], Navy students began reciting the chant as the Midshipmen won 28\u201325. In preparation for the Army\u2013Navy Game later that year, Navy sold T-shirts with the phrase written on them.<ref name=\"U.S. soccer fans\u2019 \u2018I believe that we will win\u2019 chant started with Navy football\">{{cite news|last=Bonesteel|first=Matt|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/soccer-insider/wp/2014/07/01/u-s-soccer-fans-i-believe-that-we-will-win-chant-started-with-navy-football/|title=U.S. soccer fans\u2019 \u2018I believe that we will win\u2019 chant started with Navy football|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=July 1, 2014|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref> The chant is currently performed by midshipmen in the closing stages of a victory.<ref name=\"USNA History and Traditions\" />\n\nThe chant eventually spread to other college sports, with fans of the [[Utah State Aggies men's basketball]] team adopting its usage in 2009.<ref name=\"'I believe that we will win' could be trademarked by San Diego State\">{{cite news|last=Stephens|first=Matt|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/college/2014/07/07/i-believe-that-we-will-win-chant-could-be-trademarked-by-san-diego-state/12289091/|title='I believe that we will win' could be trademarked by San Diego State|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=July 7, 2014|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref> [[The Show (SDSU student section)|The Show]] of [[San Diego State University]] and [[Harvard Crimson]] students also performed it during games. Fans of various soccer clubs have also recited it, including the [[New York Red Bulls]] of [[Major League Soccer]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Brennan|first=Eamonn|url=http://www.espn.com/blog/collegebasketballnation/post/_/id/39091/coolest-chant-in-the-country-began-at-navy|title=Coolest chant in the country began at Navy|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=November 17, 2011|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref> and French team [[FC Nantes]].<ref name=\"Bedoya leads Nantes fans in 'I believe that we will win!'\">{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/planet-futbol/2016/05/09/alejandro-bedoya-nantes-chant-i-believe-we-will-win|title=Watch: Bedoya leads Nantes fans in 'I believe that we will win!'|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=May 9, 2016|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref> During the [[2016 Ryder Cup]], \"[[U-S-A!]]\" chants by American fans interspersed with calls of \"I believe that we will win!\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Williams|first=Roddy|url=http://www.rydercup.com/news-media/europe/ryder-cup-under-way-0|title=On the first tee: Ryder Cup under way|publisher=[[Ryder Cup]]|date=September 30, 2016|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===United States soccer===\nAccording to Justin Brunken, co-founder of the U.S. soccer [[supporters' group]] [[The American Outlaws]], he first heard the chant during a 2011 U.S. soccer game in Kansas City. He described it as \"a chant that just grew from there and caught on and on. It resonated with the crowds across the country and became synonymous with what we believe in.\" It eventually became a rallying call by fans of the United States national men's soccer team (USMNT). For the 2014 FIFA World Cup, [[ESPN]] used the chant in two commercials promoting the Cup, one depicting The American Outlaws and the other featuring figures like [[Kevin Costner]], [[Ice Cube]] and [[Barry Sanders]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Eisenberg|first=Jeff|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/soccer-dirty-tackle/the-improbable-story-of-how-the-trendiest-chant-in-sports-began-040228934.html|title=The improbable story of how the trendiest chant in sports began|publisher=[[Yahoo! Sports]]|date=June 19, 2014|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref> The cheer was also acknowledged by members of the USMNT, with goalkeeper [[Tim Howard]] posting it on his [[Twitter]] and receiving almost 60,000 [[Twitter#Tweets|retweets]] during the 2014 World Cup,<ref>{{cite news|last=Hall|first=Matthew|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/opinion/the-conversation/sdut-i-believe-that-we-will-win-trademark-sdsu-2014jul07-htmlstory.html|title=SDSU may trademark 'I believe that we will win!'|newspaper=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]|date=July 7, 2014|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref> [[Alejandro Bedoya]] leading FC Nantes fans in it after home games,<ref name=\"Bedoya leads Nantes fans in 'I believe that we will win!'\" /> and former captain [[Landon Donovan]] doing so prior to the [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup]] final.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/extra-mustard/2015/07/05/landon-donovan-chant-video-uswnt-womens-world-cup|title=Landon Donovan leads 'I believe that we will win' chant before WWC final|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=July 5, 2015|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref> The [[United States women's national soccer team]] went on to win the Cup after defeating [[Japan women's national football team|Japan]].<ref name=\"USWNT leads crowd in \u2018I believe that we just won\u2019 chant\" />\n\nDuring the 2015 World Cup victory parade for the [[United States women's national soccer team]] (USWNT), forward [[Abby Wambach]] led fans in a modified call of \"I believe that we just won!\"<ref name=\"USWNT leads crowd in \u2018I believe that we just won\u2019 chant\">{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/planet-futbol/2015/07/07/uswnt-world-cup-victory-rally-chant-video|title=Watch: USWNT leads crowd in \u2018I believe that we just won\u2019 chant|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=July 7, 2015|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===San Diego State University trademark===\nStrong, who was taught the chant by Rodriguez, was later stationed in San Diego and earned his [[Master of Business Administration]] at San Diego State.<ref name=\"I believe that we will win the trademark\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbs8.com/story/25992071/i-believe-that-we-will-win-the-trademark|title=\"I believe that we will win\" the trademark|publisher=[[KFMB-TV]]|date=July 10, 2014|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref> In 2011, San Diego State clothing store Aztec Shops Ltd. attempted to trademark the phrase.<ref name=\"'I believe that we will win' could be trademarked by San Diego State\" /> Strong opposed the trademark, stating \"everybody would be best served if they removed their attempt to trademark the cheer\" and that the Naval Academy would be resisting it.<ref name=\"I believe that we will win the trademark\" /> In 2017, the [[Trademark Trial and Appeal Board]] rejected the trademark, saying it had been \"widely used over a long period of time by various groups.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Donahue|first=Bill|url=https://www.law360.com/articles/886683/ttab-won-t-register-i-believe-chant-as-trademark|title=TTAB Won't Register 'I Believe' Chant As Trademark|work=[[Law360]]|date=January 31, 2017|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Other sports===\nIn 2018, [[FiveThirtyEight]] referenced the chant in the title of an article about American's success in recent golf tournaments.<ref>{{cite web|last=Planos|first=Josh|url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/i-believe-that-we-will-win-at-golf/|title=I Believe That We Will Win \u2026 At Golf|publisher=[[FiveThirtyEight]]|date=July 19, 2018|accessdate=July 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Non-sports usage===\nAfter the [[death of Osama bin Laden]] in 2011, the Naval Academy celebrated with Commandant [[Robert E. Clark II]]. Clark led the midshipmen in a modified chant of \"I believe that we have won!\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Davis|first=Noah|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/osama-bin-laden-us-naval-academy-dant-i-believe-2011-5|title=US Naval Academy Students Go ABSOLUTELY NUTS Celebrating Osama Bin Laden's Death [VIDEO]|publisher=[[Business Insider]]|date=May 2, 2011|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe chant has also seen use in protest, such as during the [[Occupy Wall Street]] march in 2011. The Florida-based organization [[Dream Defenders]] adopted the phrase for protests following the 2012 [[shooting of Trayvon Martin]], used during a protest at the Florida state capital in 2012.<ref>{{cite news|last=Alvarez|first=Lisette|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/12/us/dream-defenders-arent-walking-out-on-their-florida-protest.html|title=Florida Sit-In Against \u2018Stand Your Ground\u2019|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=August 11, 2013|accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref> Phil Agnew of the Dream Defenders also led the chant during the 50th anniversary of the \"March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom\" in 2013, leading to its nationwide prominence during [[Black Lives Matter]] protests between 2012\u20132016.<ref>{{cite web|last=Morrison|first=Aaron|url=https://www.mic.com/articles/166084/black-lives-matter-inaugurates-four-years-of-resistance-with-anti-trump-disruption-protest|title=Black Lives Matter inaugurates four years of resistance with anti-Trump disruption protest|publisher=[[Mic (media company)|Mic]]|date=January 20, 2016|accessdate=February 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn April of 2020, Cuban-American rapper [[Pitbull (rapper)|Pitbull]] released a promotional single titled \"I Believe We Will Win\" (which samples the \"I believe that we will win!\" chant) in response to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]. The song inspires those affected by the COVID-19 outbreak to lift themselves up and rise above the situation. An accompanying music video was also released. Pitbull is donating all proceeds from song sales, streaming, and views to COVID-19 affiliated nonprofits.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/03/listen-to-pitbulls-new-song-i-believe-we-will-win.html|title=Pitbull Delivers a Message of Hope in New Coronavirus Jam|last=Sinha|first=Charu|work=Mashable|access-date=2020-03-28|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Sports}}\n* [[Football chant]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{United States men's national soccer team}}\n{{Navy Midshipmen football navbox}}\n{{Navy Midshipmen men's soccer navbox}}\n\n[[Category:Football songs and chants]]\n[[Category:Association football culture]]\n[[Category:United States men's national soccer team]]\n[[Category:Navy Midshipmen]]\n", "name_user": "Skullkrane", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNon-sports usage:Pitbull", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I_believe_that_we_will_win!"}
{"title_page": "Huilliche uprising of 1792", "text_new": "{{infobox military conflict\n|conflict    =Huilliche uprising of 1792\n|partof      =\n|image       =\n|caption     = \n|date        =September 1792\u201314 January 1793\n|place       =[[Futahuillimapu]], [[Zona Sur|southern Chile]]\n|coordinates =\n|map_type    =\n|map_relief  =\n|latitude    =\n|longitude   =\n|map_size    =\n|map_marksize =\n|map_caption =\n|map_label   =\n|territory   = Huilliches recognise Spanish sovereignity over [[Futahuillimapu]] but retain some rights\n|result      = Uprising supressed \n|status      =\n|combatants_header =\n|combatant1  ={{flagicon|Spain|1786}} [[Spanish Empire]]\n|combatant2  =[[Huilliche people|Huilliches]] of [[Futahuillimapu]]\n|commander1  = {{flagicon|Spain|1786}} [[Tom\u00e1s de Figueroa]]\n|commander2  =\n|strength1   =\n|strength2   =\n|casualties1 =\n|casualties2 =\n|notes       =\n|campaignbox = {{Campaignbox Spanish colonial campaigns}}\n}}\nThe '''Huilliche uprising of 1792''' was an indigenous uprising against the Spanish penetration into [[Futahuillimapu]], territory in [[Zona Sur|southern Chile]] that had been ''de facto'' free of Spanish rule [[Destruction of the Seven Cities|since 1602]]. The first part of the conflict was a series of Huilliche attacks on Spanish settlers and missions in the frontier next to [[Bueno River]]. Following this a militia in charge of [[Tom\u00e1s de Figueroa]] departed from [[Valdivia]] ravaging Huilliche territory in a quest to punish those involved in the attacks.\n\n==Background==\n{{Location map+|Chile|float=right|width=300|caption=The location of Spanish settlements and forts within the modern boundaries of Chile and Argentina. In red is the land of Cuncos and Huilliches where the Spanish aimed to build a road to conect Valdivia with the settlements to the south.|places=\n<!-- North-East-->\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-29.9 |long=-71.25 |label=|position=left|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-32.883333 |long=-68.816667 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-33.45 |long=-70.666667 |label=[[Santiago]]|position=left|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-36.623889 |long=-72.135833 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-36.733333 |long=-72.983333 |label=|position=left|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-37.25 |long=-73.316667 |label=|position=left|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-37.5 |long=-72.666667 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-41.866667 |long=-73.833333 |label=[[Ancud]]|position=left|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-39.890556 |long=-73.393333 |label=[[Valdivia]]|position=left|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-40.780582 |long=-73.521265 |label=[[Futahuillimapu]]|position=left|Cercle rouge 100%.svg\n |marksize=20}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-40.316667 |long=-72.966667 |label=[[Bueno River]]|position=right|mark=Blue pog.svg|label_size=90}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-41.745833 |long=-73.706389 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-42.466667 |long=-73.8 |label=|position=left|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n}}\nBeginning in the mid-18th century the Spanish enclave of [[Valdivia]] begun a period of agricultural expansion. The expansion, that mainly directed to the south, was done mostly by pacific means, but hostilities with indigenous Huilliches did occur.<ref name=CouyoUrbina/> The expansion of Valdivia included a process of [[mestizo|mestization]] and the purchasing of indigenous lands by [[criollo people|criollo]]s and transformation of previous indigenous proprietors into [[inquilino]]s.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Illanes Oliva |first=M. Ang\u00e9lica |date=2014 |title=La cuarta frontera. El caso del territorio valdiviano (Chile, XVII\u2013XIX) |url=http://www.scielo.cl/scielo.php?script=sci_arttext&pid=S0718-04622014000100013&lng=es&nrm=iso&tlng=es |journal=[[Atenea]] |publisher= |volume=509 |issue= |pages=227\u2013243 |doi= |access-date=30 January 2016}}</ref> In contrast the Spanish settlement at Chilo\u00e9 Archipelago had a history of conflicts with the indigenous peoples north of the archipelago. After the Valdivian colonization had reached [[Bueno River]] Spanish authorities pushed for connecting the city of Valdivia with the settlements at [[Chacao Channel]] by a road. This way the Spanish authorities hoped to make its possible for Valdivia and Chilo\u00e9 to offer each other mutual aid in the case of an [[Coastal defence of colonial Chile|invasion by a European power]].<ref name=CouyoUrbina>{{cite journal |last=Couyoumdjian |first=Juan Ricardo |date=2009 |title=Rese\u00f1a de \"La frontera de arriba en Chile colonial. Interacci\u00f3n hispano-ind\u00edgena en el territorio entre Valdivia y Chilo\u00e9 e imaginario de sus bordes geogr\u00e1ficos, 1600-1800\" de MAR\u00cdA XIMENA URBINA CARRASCO |url=http://www.redalyc.org/pdf/334/33411422021.pdf |journal=[[Historia (history of the Americas journal)|Historia]] |publisher= |volume=I |issue=42 |pages=281\u2013283 |doi= |access-date=30 January 2016}}</ref> In the 1780s when attempting to cooperate to establish the road the Governor of Valdivia and the Intandant of Chilo\u00e9 disagreed. The [[Governorate of Chilo\u00e9|Intendant of Chilo\u00e9]] [[Francisco Hurtado del Pino]] preferred to militarily confront the Huilliches, while Governor of Valdivia [[Mariano Pusterla]] did not.<ref name=Arana49>Barros Arana 2000, p. 49.</ref> As Hurtado del Pino was removed from his position and replaced by [[Francisco Garos]] cooperation ensued.<ref name=Arana49/> On October 1788 Pusterla sent an expedition to traverse the Huilliche-ruled territories to reach Chilo\u00e9. The expedition preved successful and by February 1789 the men were back in Valdivia.<ref name=Arana50>Barros Arana 2000, p. 50.</ref> Pusterla subsequently arranged to improve the path to Chilo\u00e9, in particularly to widen it at places is was a narrow path along forests.<ref name=Arana50/> In a parliament with local Cuncos and Huilliches Pusterla assured the opening of the path along there would not imply a reestablishment of the city of Osorno.<ref name=Arana50/> The transit along this road depended on the goodwill of the local tribes.<ref name=Arana50/>\n\n==Uprising==\nThe uprising begun in September 1792, with a series of assaults against Spanish settlers in [[R\u00edo Bueno, Chile|R\u00edo Bueno]] and [[Lago Ranco, Chile|Lago Ranco]].<ref name=Arana65>Barros Arana 2000, p. 65.</ref> Houses were torched and animals stolen. Ten Spanish settlers are reported to have been killed.<ref name=Arana65/> Spanish messengers and priests cought off guard and brutally killed.<ref name=Arana66>Barros Arana 2000, p. 66.</ref> Spanish refugees escaped north reaching Valdivia.<ref name=Arana66/> Once authorities realised it was an uprising and not ordinary crime a detachment in charge of [[Tom\u00e1s de Figueroa]] was sent south from Valdivia on October 3, following [[Futa River]].<ref name=Arana66/> The first step of the campaign was to [[Daglipulli]] where the militia of Figeroa was to absorb the 22 soldiers stationed to reach a total of 104 men.<ref name=Arana66/>\n\nWhen Figueroa reached the conflict zone the local Huilliches presented themselves as friends.<ref name=Arana67>Barros Arana 2000, p. 67.</ref> Deeming this to be a tactic to avoid retribution Figueroa had local [[cacique]] [[Manquep\u00e1n]] executed along his two sons and seventeen of his men.<ref name=Arana67/> These men rejected baptism before their death.<ref name=Arana68>Barros Arana 2000, p. 68.</ref> Subsequently, the Spanish took custody of women and children, while animals were confiscated.<ref name=Arana69>Barros Arana 2000, p. 69.</ref> Next on the militia continued to cross [[Bueno River]]. Thereafter it advanced slowly amidst heavy rains, obstacles put in their way and minor ambushes.<ref name=Arana69/> Figueroa reached the ruins of Osorno on November 22, the view of which made a strong impression on him.<ref name=Arana69/> The campaign continued to ravage Huilliche territory in pursuit of rebel elements until it arrived back to Valdivia on January 14, 1793.<ref name=Arana70>Barros Arana 2000, p. 70.</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nAfter the Spanish had suppressed an uprising by the Mapuche-Huilliches [[Royal Governor of Chile]] [[Ambrosio O'Higgins, 1st Marquis of Osorno|Ambrosio O'Higgins]] summoned local chiefs to the [[Parliament of Las Canoas]].<ref name=Alcaman>{{cite web |title=El parlamento general de Las Canoas |last1=Alcam\u00e1n |first1=Eugenio |date= |url=http://futahuillimapu.org |publisher= |quote=|language=Spanish}}</ref> The parliament is historically relevant since the treaty signed at the end of the meeting allowed the Spanish to reestablish the city of Osorno{{efn-ua|The city of Osorno had originally been founded by the Spanish in 1558 but was destroyed by Mapuche-Huilliches in 1602 during the [[destruction of the Seven Cities]].}} and secure the transit rights between [[Valdivia]] and the \u00bfSpanish mainland settlements next to [[Chilo\u00e9 Archipelago]] ([[Carelmapu]]). The indigenous signatories recognized the king of Spain as their sovereign but they kept considerable autonomy in the lands they did not ceded.<ref name=Painemal2010>{{cite journal |last=Contreras Painemal |first=Carlos |date=2011 |title=Los Tratados celebrados por los Mapuche con la Corona Espa\u00f1ola, la Rep\u00fablica de Chile y la Rep\u00fablica de Argentina  |url=http://d-nb.info/1026265320/34 |journal= |publisher= |volume= |issue= |pages= |doi= |accessdate=3 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist-ua}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*{{cite book\n | last       = Barros Arana\n | first      = Diego\n | author-link1 = Diego Barros Arana \n | title      = Historia General de Chile\n | volume     = VII\n | url        = http://www.memoriachilena.gob.cl/602/w3-article-9008.html\n | year       = 2000\n | origyear   = 1884\n | edition    = 2\n | publisher  = [[Editorial Universitaria]]\n | location   = Santiago, Chile\n | isbn       = 956-11-1535-2 \n | ref        = harv\n | language   = Spanish\n |chapter = Cap\u00edtulo XVII\n  }}\n\n[[Category:History of Los R\u00edos Region]]\n[[Category:History of Los Lagos Region]]\n[[Category:Battles involving the Mapuche]]\n[[Category:Indigenous rebellions against the Spanish Empire]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1792]]\n[[Category:1792 in the Captaincy General of Chile]]\n[[Category:Rebellions in Chile]]\n[[Category:Huilliche history|Uprising]]\n", "text_old": "{{infobox military conflict\n|conflict    =Huilliche uprising of 1792\n|partof      =\n|image       =\n|caption     = \n|date        =September 1792\u201314 January 1793\n|place       =[[Futahuillimapu]], [[Zona Sur|southern Chile]]\n|coordinates =\n|map_type    =\n|map_relief  =\n|latitude    =\n|longitude   =\n|map_size    =\n|map_marksize =\n|map_caption =\n|map_label   =\n|territory   = Huilliches recognise Spanish sovereignity over [[Futahuillimapu]] but retain some rights\n|result      = Uprising supressed \n|status      =\n|combatants_header =\n|combatant1  ={{flagicon|Spain|1786}} [[Spanish Empire]]\n|combatant2  =[[Huilliche people|Huilliches]] of [[Futahuillimapu]]\n|commander1  = {{flagicon|Spain|1786}} [[Tom\u00e1s de Figueroa]]\n|commander2  =\n|strength1   =\n|strength2   =\n|casualties1 =\n|casualties2 =\n|notes       =\n|campaignbox = {{Campaignbox Spanish colonial campaigns}}\n}}\nThe '''Huilliche uprising of 1792''' was an indigenous uprising against the Spanish penetration into [[Futahuillimpu]], territory in [[Zona Sur|southern Chile]] that had been ''de facto'' free of Spanish rule [[Destruction of the Seven Cities|since 1602]]. The first part of the conflict was a series of Huilliche attacks on Spanish settlers and missions in the frontier next to [[Bueno River]]. Following this a militia in charge of [[Tom\u00e1s de Figueroa]] departed from [[Valdivia]] ravaging Huilliche territory in a quest to punish those involved in the attacks.\n\n==Background==\n{{Location map+|Chile|float=right|width=300|caption=The location of Spanish settlements and forts within the modern boundaries of Chile and Argentina. In red is the land of Cuncos and Huilliches where the Spanish aimed to build a road to conect Valdivia with the settlements to the south.|places=\n<!-- North-East-->\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-29.9 |long=-71.25 |label=|position=left|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-32.883333 |long=-68.816667 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-33.45 |long=-70.666667 |label=[[Santiago]]|position=left|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-36.623889 |long=-72.135833 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-36.733333 |long=-72.983333 |label=|position=left|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-37.25 |long=-73.316667 |label=|position=left|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-37.5 |long=-72.666667 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-41.866667 |long=-73.833333 |label=[[Ancud]]|position=left|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-39.890556 |long=-73.393333 |label=[[Valdivia]]|position=left|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-40.780582 |long=-73.521265 |label=[[Futahuillimapu]]|position=left|Cercle rouge 100%.svg\n |marksize=20}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-40.316667 |long=-72.966667 |label=[[Bueno River]]|position=right|mark=Blue pog.svg|label_size=90}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-41.745833 |long=-73.706389 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-42.466667 |long=-73.8 |label=|position=left|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n}}\nBeginning in the mid-18th century the Spanish enclave of [[Valdivia]] begun a period of agricultural expansion. The expansion, that mainly directed to the south, was done mostly by pacific means, but hostilities with indigenous Huilliches did occur.<ref name=CouyoUrbina/> The expansion of Valdivia included a process of [[mestizo|mestization]] and the purchasing of indigenous lands by [[criollo people|criollo]]s and transformation of previous indigenous proprietors into [[inquilino]]s.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Illanes Oliva |first=M. Ang\u00e9lica |date=2014 |title=La cuarta frontera. El caso del territorio valdiviano (Chile, XVII\u2013XIX) |url=http://www.scielo.cl/scielo.php?script=sci_arttext&pid=S0718-04622014000100013&lng=es&nrm=iso&tlng=es |journal=[[Atenea]] |publisher= |volume=509 |issue= |pages=227\u2013243 |doi= |access-date=30 January 2016}}</ref> In contrast the Spanish settlement at Chilo\u00e9 Archipelago had a history of conflicts with the indigenous peoples north of the archipelago. After the Valdivian colonization had reached [[Bueno River]] Spanish authorities pushed for connecting the city of Valdivia with the settlements at [[Chacao Channel]] by a road. This way the Spanish authorities hoped to make its possible for Valdivia and Chilo\u00e9 to offer each other mutual aid in the case of an [[Coastal defence of colonial Chile|invasion by a European power]].<ref name=CouyoUrbina>{{cite journal |last=Couyoumdjian |first=Juan Ricardo |date=2009 |title=Rese\u00f1a de \"La frontera de arriba en Chile colonial. Interacci\u00f3n hispano-ind\u00edgena en el territorio entre Valdivia y Chilo\u00e9 e imaginario de sus bordes geogr\u00e1ficos, 1600-1800\" de MAR\u00cdA XIMENA URBINA CARRASCO |url=http://www.redalyc.org/pdf/334/33411422021.pdf |journal=[[Historia (history of the Americas journal)|Historia]] |publisher= |volume=I |issue=42 |pages=281\u2013283 |doi= |access-date=30 January 2016}}</ref> In the 1780s when attempting to cooperate to establish the road the Governor of Valdivia and the Intandant of Chilo\u00e9 disagreed. The [[Governorate of Chilo\u00e9|Intendant of Chilo\u00e9]] [[Francisco Hurtado del Pino]] preferred to militarily confront the Huilliches, while Governor of Valdivia [[Mariano Pusterla]] did not.<ref name=Arana49>Barros Arana 2000, p. 49.</ref> As Hurtado del Pino was removed from his position and replaced by [[Francisco Garos]] cooperation ensued.<ref name=Arana49/> On October 1788 Pusterla sent an expedition to traverse the Huilliche-ruled territories to reach Chilo\u00e9. The expedition preved successful and by February 1789 the men were back in Valdivia.<ref name=Arana50>Barros Arana 2000, p. 50.</ref> Pusterla subsequently arranged to improve the path to Chilo\u00e9, in particularly to widen it at places is was a narrow path along forests.<ref name=Arana50/> In a parliament with local Cuncos and Huilliches Pusterla assured the opening of the path along there would not imply a reestablishment of the city of Osorno.<ref name=Arana50/> The transit along this road depended on the goodwill of the local tribes.<ref name=Arana50/>\n\n==Uprising==\nThe uprising begun in September 1792, with a series of assaults against Spanish settlers in [[R\u00edo Bueno, Chile|R\u00edo Bueno]] and [[Lago Ranco, Chile|Lago Ranco]].<ref name=Arana65>Barros Arana 2000, p. 65.</ref> Houses were torched and animals stolen. Ten Spanish settlers are reported to have been killed.<ref name=Arana65/> Spanish messengers and priests cought off guard and brutally killed.<ref name=Arana66>Barros Arana 2000, p. 66.</ref> Spanish refugees escaped north reaching Valdivia.<ref name=Arana66/> Once authorities realised it was an uprising and not ordinary crime a detachment in charge of [[Tom\u00e1s de Figueroa]] was sent south from Valdivia on October 3, following [[Futa River]].<ref name=Arana66/> The first step of the campaign was to [[Daglipulli]] where the militia of Figeroa was to absorb the 22 soldiers stationed to reach a total of 104 men.<ref name=Arana66/>\n\nWhen Figueroa reached the conflict zone the local Huilliches presented themselves as friends.<ref name=Arana67>Barros Arana 2000, p. 67.</ref> Deeming this to be a tactic to avoid retribution Figueroa had local [[cacique]] [[Manquep\u00e1n]] executed along his two sons and seventeen of his men.<ref name=Arana67/> These men rejected baptism before their death.<ref name=Arana68>Barros Arana 2000, p. 68.</ref> Subsequently, the Spanish took custody of women and children, while animals were confiscated.<ref name=Arana69>Barros Arana 2000, p. 69.</ref> Next on the militia continued to cross [[Bueno River]]. Thereafter it advanced slowly amidst heavy rains, obstacles put in their way and minor ambushes.<ref name=Arana69/> Figueroa reached the ruins of Osorno on November 22, the view of which made a strong impression on him.<ref name=Arana69/> The campaign continued to ravage Huilliche territory in pursuit of rebel elements until it arrived back to Valdivia on January 14, 1793.<ref name=Arana70>Barros Arana 2000, p. 70.</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nAfter the Spanish had suppressed an uprising by the Mapuche-Huilliches [[Royal Governor of Chile]] [[Ambrosio O'Higgins, 1st Marquis of Osorno|Ambrosio O'Higgins]] summoned local chiefs to the [[Parliament of Las Canoas]].<ref name=Alcaman>{{cite web |title=El parlamento general de Las Canoas |last1=Alcam\u00e1n |first1=Eugenio |date= |url=http://futahuillimapu.org |publisher= |quote=|language=Spanish}}</ref> The parliament is historically relevant since the treaty signed at the end of the meeting allowed the Spanish to reestablish the city of Osorno{{efn-ua|The city of Osorno had originally been founded by the Spanish in 1558 but was destroyed by Mapuche-Huilliches in 1602 during the [[destruction of the Seven Cities]].}} and secure the transit rights between [[Valdivia]] and the \u00bfSpanish mainland settlements next to [[Chilo\u00e9 Archipelago]] ([[Carelmapu]]). The indigenous signatories recognized the king of Spain as their sovereign but they kept considerable autonomy in the lands they did not ceded.<ref name=Painemal2010>{{cite journal |last=Contreras Painemal |first=Carlos |date=2011 |title=Los Tratados celebrados por los Mapuche con la Corona Espa\u00f1ola, la Rep\u00fablica de Chile y la Rep\u00fablica de Argentina  |url=http://d-nb.info/1026265320/34 |journal= |publisher= |volume= |issue= |pages= |doi= |accessdate=3 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist-ua}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*{{cite book\n | last       = Barros Arana\n | first      = Diego\n | author-link1 = Diego Barros Arana \n | title      = Historia General de Chile\n | volume     = VII\n | url        = http://www.memoriachilena.gob.cl/602/w3-article-9008.html\n | year       = 2000\n | origyear   = 1884\n | edition    = 2\n | publisher  = [[Editorial Universitaria]]\n | location   = Santiago, Chile\n | isbn       = 956-11-1535-2 \n | ref        = harv\n | language   = Spanish\n |chapter = Cap\u00edtulo XVII\n  }}\n\n[[Category:History of Los R\u00edos Region]]\n[[Category:History of Los Lagos Region]]\n[[Category:Battles involving the Mapuche]]\n[[Category:Indigenous rebellions against the Spanish Empire]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1792]]\n[[Category:1792 in the Captaincy General of Chile]]\n[[Category:Rebellions in Chile]]\n[[Category:Huilliche history|Uprising]]\n", "name_user": "Sietecolores", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Huilliche_uprising_of_1792"}
